We all knew that at some point our summer rally would be ruined by renewed trade fears…and today it happened.
The White House unveiled new tariffs on China last night, which stopped the market's four-day winning streak in its tracks and led to a more than 200-point dip in the Dow.
All of the major indices were on a roll following the Fourth of July holiday, but the Dow's ascent was most noteworthy since it takes trade turmoil the hardest.
However, today's news of 10% tariffs on $200 billion worth of Chinese goods pulled the index down by 0.88% (or about 220 points) to 24700.5.
The S&P's quest for 2800 is put on hold for now, as the index slipped 0.71% (or nearly 20 points) to 2774.
And the NASDAQ was off 0.55% to 7716.6.
Fortunately, the tariffs won't go into effect until August, so the U.S. and China have time to work something out if that's what they want to do.
"There's no question that the lingering fears surrounding the potential trade war are having a larger impact on the S&P 500 than the domestically inclined Russell 2000.
But today's resilience actually took me by surprise," said Dave Bartosiak, editor of Surprise Trader , Momentum Trader and Blockchain Innovators .
"A week or two ago, headlines like we got last night would have dropped the market over 1%.
Today, stubborn bulls kept coming in and buying dips but the depths of the offers were just too great to overcome," he continued.
Three portfolios bought on Wednesday.
Counterstrike added a luxury furniture company that's pulled back and sold another position for a double-digit return.
Surprise Trader made it three buys in three days with the addition of a transportation company that reports next week, while Home Run Investor got some exposure to the Internet content area.

Learn more about all these moves in the highlights section below:

Counterstrike: If you're looking to spend $2500 for a coffee table, then you're well aware of RH (RH).
This home furnishing marketplace sells luxury items, and its having no problem attracting customers with deep pockets as it beat the Zacks Consensus Estimate by 32% in its last report.
Right now though, RH is off its highs by about $35 and unbelievably still has short interest of about 46%.
Jeremy thinks this stock is all set for another jump higher, so he added the stock on Wednesday with a 7% allocation.
He plans to bring it to a full position when the Fib retracement is complete at about $120-$122.
The editor also sold Salesforce.com (CRM) for a 25% return in a little over 3 months.
Read the complete commentary for more.
Surprise Trader: When the economy's really chugging along, you can bet the transportation space is also on the right track.
For his third pick in as many days, Dave capitalized on this high demand with a 12.5% allocation in GATX Corp. (GATX).
This leading global railcar lessor is part of the transportation - equipment & leasing space, which places it in the top 6% of the Zacks Industry Rank.
The company has a positive Earnings ESP heading into the quarterly report on Thursday, July 19.
Last time, GATX beat by 69%...and the editor expects another good performance next week.
Read the full write-up for more.
Home Run Investor: On Wednesday, Brian Bolan said "I do" to XO Group (XOXO), an Internet content company that owns personal wedding planner site TheKnot.com.
It also runs sites called The Nest and The Bump for help in home buying and pregnancy.
The editor believes this company's content is perfect for the millennial crowd…and its earnings history bears that out.
In the past four quarters, XOXO has beaten three times and met once, amassing an average surprise of 148% in that time.
Most recently, it topped by 550%!
Read the complete commentary for more on this new addition.
In other news, the portfolio is now at 15 names, but Brian is looking to get up to 20 positions.
So be ready for more buys in the near future.
